A15. Discover 5 recent security incidents.

FBI Surveillance System Cyberattack (USA)
What happened: A cyberattack targeted systems used for wiretapping and investigations by the Federal Bureau of Investigation
Impact: Classified as a “major incident” due to risks to national security
Details: Attackers accessed sensitive infrastructure; origin still unknown
Why it matters: Shows that even top government agencies are vulnerable to advanced cyber threats

European Commission Data Breach (EU)
What happened: Hackers breached cloud systems linked to the EU’s official websites
Target: European Commission
Impact: Data was stolen (estimated hundreds of GB), though core systems remained safe
Cause: Likely compromised cloud account (possibly via malware or social engineering)
Why it matters: Highlights risks of cloud security and credential theft

Axios npm Supply Chain Attack
What happened: Attackers compromised the npm account of Axios
Impact: Malicious versions distributed malware (Remote Access Trojan) to developers
Scope: Affected Windows, macOS, and Linux users
Technique: Software supply chain attack (infecting trusted libraries)
Why it matters: Demonstrates how attackers target developers and dependencies instead of end users

Northern Ireland School IT System Attack
What happened: Cyberattack on the C2K education network used by schools
Impact: Thousands of students unable to access study materials during exams
Response: System shutdown, password resets, and investigation
Why it matters: Shows cyberattacks can disrupt education and daily life, not just businesses

Iran-Linked Cyber Warfare & Spyware Campaign
What happened: Iran-linked hackers launched cyberattacks including spyware via mobile messages
Targets: Civilians, healthcare systems, and organizations
Impact: Data theft, surveillance, and disruption of services
Scale: Thousands of attacks reported as part of ongoing cyber warfare
Why it matters: Cyberattacks are increasingly part of modern warfare and geopolitical conflict
